args: Bored, bored, BORED! ...Curran!\nBring me an interesting case at once!
Just tucker down there, tiger.\nCases don't grow on trees, you know.
...I just had a thought. What if you became\na criminal and CREATED a case for me?
That is a terrible idea. Maybe you need\na new hobby that doesn't require someone\nto break the law. ...Huh?
Well, well. It looks like you might get\nyour wish granted after all.
How fine to see such an unusual face\nin our midst. After all, rare guests often\nbring fascinating mysteries with them!
Well, you haven't changed one bit.\nAnd though it pains me to say this,\nwe...need your help.
Oh my. This DOES sound interesting.
Interesting for you, perhaps!\nFor us, it is terribly serious.
You'll have to excuse Heinwald—\npretend he has some sort of illness.\nNow, please tell us what's going on.
It all started a few days ago when the\nprince was invited to a nobleman's manor.
Some of us went with him, but we left\nearly and he ended up heading back alone.
Apparently, he noticed a ring with a\nred jewel lying near the nobleman's\ngate as he was about to leave.
He then went back to the manor\nto see if anyone had lost it.
The daughter of the nobleman claimed\nto know nothing of the ring, and told\nHis Highness to keep it.
Fascinating. What did he do next?
Seeing no other option, he returned to\nthe Halidom with the ring.
But the next day, the nobleman came to\nthe castle and demanded the ring's return.
These guys can't make up their minds.\nI assume he returned it, right?
Not exactly. You see, the nobleman\ndemanded the return of his heirloom,\nwhich is a ring with a BLUE stone.
Ah. And the one he picked up held\na red stone, correct?
Right. The prince told the nobleman he\ndidn't know anything about a blue ring,\nbut...
It seems they are laboring under the\nimpression that {player_name}\nstole the blue ring.
＂How dare you give something so cheap!\nAre you mocking us?＂ he shouted\nthreateningly.

After a bit, the prince agreed to accompany
him back to the manor to try and work the
entire situation out—but once they arrived,
he found himself under house arrest.
Please, Heinwald. You must help us clear\nHis Highness's name!
You have nothing to worry about;\nI have already solved the problem.
I have but a single question:\nWhere is the red-jeweled ring\nthe prince brought back with him?
If my suspicion is correct, there should\nbe some words engraved on it.\n...Words of love, to be exact.
Oh, look! There IS text there!\nIt says, ＂I grant you my love eternal.＂
Quite so! Then the matter is solved. \nI will bring the culprit to heel,\nso please wait here.
Er, who exactly is this person?
The rapscallion who absconded the noble's\nmanor with the blue-gemmed ring.
Glad we pulled it off him before he\ncould hawk it on the black market.
How in the world did you find\nthis man so quickly?!
The nobleman's daughter told the prince\nto keep the ring, yes?

And yet, she ALSO told him she knew
nothing about it. If that was the case,
how could she have been so certain
it didn't belong to someone there?
She made a decision to let the prince\ntake the ring, which means she knew\nof its origins.
So the ring belongs to...the daughter?
But that makes no sense. Why would she\nallow him to walk away with her own ring?
That forms the crux of this entire matter.
Why would this girl have told a stranger\nto take her own ring away?
There can only be one answer:\nThe ring was cast away intentionally.
She did not wish to lay eyes upon it again.
This is a rather typical state of affairs,\nto be honest—and it makes this\nsomething of a typical case.
Sounds like love trouble to me!
Indeed. Mostlike the ring holds memories\nof a person that the woman does not\nwish to remember.
So she threw away her memories...
That explains the red-jeweled ring,\nbut then what about the blue one?

The ring was full of memories of another.
Yet it belonged not to another, but to her.
From that, we can assume where the red
ring came from.
A present from a lover, right?
Exactly. Knowing that much, we can now\nascertain the whereabouts of the blue one.
The daughter gave it to someone\nin exchange for the red one?
Just so. And with her having cast it aside,\nit seems safe to say that relationship was\nnot successful.

Furthermore, I would venture to guess that
the red ring is a cheap article, while the
blue one is the noble's family heirloom.
Which would mean...?
Some bag of sleaze wanted that ring\nand tricked the daughter to get it!\nOf all the lowdown...

Exactly! So if we go looking for people
who have been cozy of late with the
daughter before mysteriously vanishing,
we should find our culprit.
*sigh* So the prince was just a bystander\nwho got caught up in this ruse.
Indubitably. Incidentally, I believe the lord\nof the manor mistook the prince for his\ndaughter's one-time paramour.

His anger over the prince trying to give her
＂something cheap＂ is likely due to the fact
that he thought the ring was intended as a
gift for his daughter.
We need to sort THAT out right now!
Well, if we don't bring this guy and the\nring, it'll all be pointless. C'mon, you!
And with that, another case is closed.\nHowever, it seems this castle has no\nshortage of mysteries that need solved.
This is bad! Bad, bad, baaaad!\n...Hey, wait. Where is everybody?
It seems they are all rather busy.\nHowever, do you have a case that\nneeds solving, Notte?
Ha ha! Fortune smiles on me this day!
I KNEW this castle was chock full of\npleasant cases. Permit me then, if you\nwill, to impose here for a little while.
This is NOT something to be happy about!
Yes, yes. Now please explain the\nsituation to me in detail...
